despread, variety of healer. This book examines the work of Kaqchikel and Tz'utujiil Maya bonesetters, analyzes how they diagnose and treat injuries, and contrasts the empirical and sacred approaches of various healers. Hinojosa shows how bonesetters are carefully adapting certain biomedical technologies to meet local expectations for care and concludes that, despite pressures and criticisms from the biomedical community, bonesetting remains culturally meaningful and vital to Maya people, even if its future remains uncertain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBonesetterszGuatemala. 0aManipulation (Therapeutics)zGuatemala. 0aMaya healerszGuatemala. 0aMayasxMedicinezGuatemala. 0aTraditional medicinezGuatemala. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aHinojosa, Servando G.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32028040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477320303423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781477320303.jpg  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK